<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>draught of ro owns sunstrike even without focus items. -Zuratuli<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If SS was focused and DoR was not, DoR would be 4.13 dmg/mana and SS would be 5.17 dmg/mana. - Gwideon<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>your damage to mana is inaccurate for both spells especially Sunstrike. - Zuratuli<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sunstrike 450 mana - 45 mana (10% for 200 Specialization) = 405 mana - 60.75 mana (for 15% focus) = 343.75 mana (344)<br>
--------------1615 dmg + 161.5 (20% variable focus - avg 10%) = 1776.5 dmg (1777)<br>
1777 damage / 344 mana = 5.1657 damage/mana (5.17)<br>
<br>
Draught of Ro 255 mana - 25.5 (10% for 200 Specialization)  = 229.5 mana (230)<br>
950 dmg /230 mana  = 4.1304 damage/mana (4.13)<br>
<br>
I apologize for not detailing the math behind my numbers initially.  I only wanted to point out, that if you had trouble obtaining level 4 focus items, DoR's only advantage is in it's resists, a point which you seemed to disagree with.  I don't think level 4 mage summoned focus is that hard to obtain. But, if you can not find them and you already have level 3 focus, then you may be better off using Sunstrike.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Your argument is still flawed though as not all nukes were intended to get into the hands of all players. - Zuratuli<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
GSS was intended to filter down to lower status wizards eventually. If it were not so, it would have been named Ancient and be no-drop. GSS rightfully belonged to the top-end players when this was the premier nuke in the game. This is not true anymore. I never raised any objection when it was, I was content to wait as that was balanced. When another class is given a spell off of a vendor that so closely compares to GSS and at relatively the same level, then it became unbalanced. Any solution that does not put a comparable nuke within reach of the average player does not address the issue. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Sorry, but if your unwilling to abandon pre-pop content as XP locations then congratulations you will most likely be in the large pool of people who never get GSS and EER. - Zuratuli<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Here is the Catch-22.  In order for the average Wizard to get GSS, you have to no longer need it.  How silly is that? The general consensus seems to be that once you have AT and SoS, you will not memorize EER and GSS.  But, if you get the levels and spells in PoP then you have the possibility to acquire the spells that you will no longer need.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Pursueing levels post 60 does not force you to abandon pre pop content... You just won't be rewarded as nicely with xp. Consider it a loot based camp instead =) - Zuratuli<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I guess you need to ask yourself what makes you gaming time fun?  I have the most enjoyment when I am grouping and raiding and the task is a challenge.  Smaller and family style guilds often recruit lower level members in hopes that once they make friends with guild members they may stay instead of abandoning the guild for end-game guilds.  Where do you get experience groups?  Who do you raid with?  Mostly with your guild and friends, sometimes a pickup group.  If your friends are in the 50 - 61 level range, then leveling beyond 61 is going to green out many prime experience locations.  <br>
<br>
Yes, leveling would make farming easier.  Farming is not a challenge and not fun.  How often can you go blow Emperor Crush to pieces before it drives you bonkers?  How long will the new expansion hold your interest if it is not a challenge?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Look, I think the main thing that having Firebolt of Tallon on a vendor did was actually succeed in fixing the perception of mages as &quot;significant damage dealers.&quot; Perception is a major factor in actual groupability, and the big nukes and crits did the job of kicking mages to the front of the line. Which I think may well have been Sony's intention. - Razamatazz<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Aye, it is about time the Magician got the respect he deserved all along.  I think the adjustments made to pets, and the spell additions have done wonders for the perception of the Magician and pet classes in general.  /applaud<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I agree that it must sting many wizards to see such a fine spell on a vendor while key wizard nukes remain nigh unobtainable. Something needs to be done. - Razamatazz<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Thank you!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   It almost seems we get more support from our Magician friends than we do from our own community.  Some are so intent on squashing anything that even resembles a whine, that they fail to recognize valid issues.  As I am sure you are aware, the majority of Wizards do not want FoT adjusted.  It has sufficient drawbacks to not be overpowering for its level.<br>
